{{Use British English|date=August 2017}} {{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}} {{Infobox football biography | name = Angus Gunn | image = France - England U19, 20150331 06.JPG | image_size = 200 | caption = Gunn playing for the [[England national under-19 football team|England U19]]s in 2015 | fullname = Angus Fraser James Gunn<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/408901 |title=Premier League clubs publish retained lists |publisher=Premier League |date=9 June 2017 |accessdate=10 August 2017}}</ref> | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1996|1|22|df=y}}<ref name=11v11>{{cite web |url=https://www.11v11.com/players/angus-gunn-239276/ |title=Angus Gunn |website=11v11.com |publisher=AFS Enterprises |accessdate=10 August 2017}}</ref> | birth_place = [[Norwich]], England | height = {{convert|1.96|m|order=flip}}<ref name=11v11/> | position = [[Goalkeeper (association football)|Goalkeeper]] | currentclub = [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] | clubnumber = 28 | youthyears1 = {{0|0000}}–2011 | youthclubs1 = [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]] | youthyears2 = 2011–2017 | youthclubs2 = [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] | years1 = 2017–2018 | clubs1 = [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] | caps1 = 0 | goals1 = 0 | years2 = 2017–2018 | clubs2 = → [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]] (loan) | caps2 = 46 | goals2 = 0 | years3 = 2018– | clubs3 = [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] | caps3 = 5 | goals3 = 0 | nationalyears1 = 2011 | nationalteam1 = [[England national under-16 football team|England U16]] | nationalcaps1 = 4 | nationalgoals1 = 0 | nationalyears2 = 2011–2013 | nationalteam2 = [[England national under-17 football team|England U17]] | nationalcaps2 = 6 | nationalgoals2 = 0 | nationalyears3 = 2014–2015 | nationalteam3 = [[England national under-19 football team|England U19]] | nationalcaps3 = 4 | nationalgoals3 = 0 | nationalyears4 = 2016 | nationalteam4 = [[England national under-20 football team|England U20]] | nationalcaps4 = 2 | nationalgoals4 = 0 | nationalyears5 = 2015– | nationalteam5 = [[England national under-21 football team|England U21]] | nationalcaps5 = 11 | nationalgoals5 = 0 | club-update = 22:41, 9 March 2019 (UTC) | nationalteam-update = 17:50, 8 November 2018 (UTC) }} '''Angus Fraser James Gunn''' (born 22 January 1996) is an English professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]] for [[Premier League]] club [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]]. He has represented England at [[England national under-21 football team|under-21]] level. He began his career at his hometown club [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]], before joining [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] in 2011, eventually signing his first professional contract in 2013.
After spending the [[2017–18 in English football|2017–18 season]] on loan at boyhood club Norwich, enjoying a good run of performances throughout the entire [[EFL Championship|Championship]] campaign, Gunn signed for Southampton in the summer of 2018, for a transfer fee of £13.5 million.
==Early life== Gunn was born in [[Norwich]], Norfolk,<ref name=11v11/> to [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]]'s former goalkeeper and manager [[Bryan Gunn|Bryan]] and artist [[Susan Gunn]].<ref name=family>{{cite news |first=Scott |last=McDermott |title=Bryan Gunn will support his son Angus even if England's No1 prospect dumps Scotland in the World Cup |url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/bryan-gunn-support-son-angus-6488047 |newspaper=Daily Record |location=Glasgow |date=21 September 2015 |accessdate=10 August 2017}}</ref> His father is originally from [[Caithness]] in the far north of Scotland.<ref name=family/>
==Club career==
===Manchester City===
====Early career==== Gunn began his career at his hometown club Norwich City, before moving to [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] in 2011, for which a tribunal decided Manchester City had to pay £250,000.<ref name="Norwich loan">{{cite news |title=Angus Gunn: Manchester City keeper rejoins Norwich City on season-long loan |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40171108 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=6 June 2017 |accessdate=20 July 2017}}</ref> He signed a three-year professional contract in June 2013.<ref>{{cite news |first=Michael |last=Bailey |title=Angus Gunn is Manchester City's newest professional keeper – but he still holds Norwich City dear |url=http://www.edp24.co.uk/sport/norwich-city/angus-gunn-is-manchester-city-s-newest-professional-keeper-but-he-still-holds-norwich-city-dear-1-2241920 |newspaper=Eastern Daily Press |location=Norwich |date=19 June 2013 |accessdate=10 August 2017}}</ref> He was named on the [[Substitute (association football)|substitutes bench]] on a number of occasions throughout the [[2016–17 Manchester City F.C. season|2016–17 season]], but did not play for Manchester City that season.<ref name="Norwich loan"/>
====Loan to Norwich City==== For the [[2017–18 Norwich City F.C. season|2017–18 season]], Gunn was [[Loan (sports)|loaned]] back to Norwich City.<ref name="Norwich loan"/> He made his first-team debut in Norwich's first match of the season, away to [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]].<ref name=sb1718/> He got his first professional football clean sheet on 16 August 2017, in a 2–0 home win over [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]] at [[Carrow Road]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/40871609 |title=Norwich City 2–0 Queens Park Rangers |publisher=BBC Sport |date=16 August 2017 |accessdate=10 September 2017}}</ref> He would ultimately be the only player to be ever present for Norwich in the league during the season, also being ever present in the [[FA Cup]] and making three appearances in the [[Carabao Cup]]. At the end of the season, Norwich fans voted him third in the Player of the Season vote behind [[James Maddison]] and [[Grant Hanley]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.canaries.co.uk/News/2018/april/maddison-pots/ |title=James Maddison voted Player of the Season|publisher=canaries.co.uk |date=28 April 2018 |accessdate=10 June 2018}}</ref>
===Southampton=== Gunn joined [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] in July 2018, signing a five-year deal with the club,<ref>{{cite news |title=Gunn completes Saints move |url=https://southamptonfc.com/news/2018-07-10/announcement-southampton-manchester-city-angus-gunn-transfer |website=saintsfc |location=Norwich |date=10 July 2018 |accessdate=10 July 2018}}</ref> for a fee estimated at £13.5 million.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Stone |first1=Simon |title=Angus Gunn: Southampton complete signing of £13.5m deal for Man City goalkeeper |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44771592 |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=10 July 2018 |date=10 July 2018}}</ref> He made his debut appearance for the club on 28 August 2018 in a [[Carabao Cup]] tie against [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]]. He made his [[Premier League]] debut on 2 January 2019, making several vital saves and keeping a clean sheet and earning the man of the match award in a 0–0 draw against [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Emons |first1=Michael |title=Chelsea 0–0 Southampton |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46682779 |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=3 January 2019 |date=2 January 2019}}</ref>
==International career== Despite his father Bryan representing [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] at international level, Angus has represented the country of his birth [[England national football team|England]] at various youth levels.<ref name="author">{{Cite news | url = https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/news-and-comment/author-of-a-different-kind-of-football-book-fighting-back-with-the-gunns-421437.html |work = [[The Independent]] | title = Author of a different kind of football book: Fighting back with the Gunns | first = Phil| last = Shaw| date =25 October 2006 | accessdate =13 May 2011}}</ref>
Gunn received his first call up to the England national team in November 2017 for a [[Exhibition game#Association football|friendly]] match against [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]], after [[Jack Butland]] withdrew from the squad with an injury.<ref>{{cite news |title=Angus Gunn: Man City goalkeeper called up by England |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41950285 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=11 November 2017 |accessdate=11 November 2017}}</ref> In March 2018, Gunn was offered the opportunity by [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] manager [[Alex McLeish]] to switch allegiances to Scotland,<ref>{{cite news |title=Man City keeper Angus Gunn is wanted by Scotland, confirms national team No2 and Celtic legend Peter Grant |url=https://www.thescottishsun.co.uk/sport/football/2387127/angus-gunn-man-city-scotland-peter-grant-england-celtic/ |work=The Scottish Sun |date=20 March 2018 |accessdate=17 June 2018}}</ref> but decided to stay with England national team, and was called up to England’s pre [[2018 World Cup]] training camp in May 2018 by [[Gareth Southgate]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Angus Gunn drafted into England World Cup plans |url=https://readnorwich.com/2018/05/18/angus-gunn-drafted-into-england-world-cup-plans/ |website=Read Norwich |date=17 May 2018 |accessdate=17 June 2018}}</ref>
