{{Infobox football biography | name = Marcus Barnes | image = | caption = | fullname = Marcus Thomas Barnes<ref>{{cite web |title=Squads for 2016/17 Premier League confirmed |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/84136 |publisher=Premier League |date=1 September 2016 |accessdate=16 January 2018}}</ref> | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1996|12|1|df=y}}<ref name="11v11">{{cite web |title=Marcus Barnes |url=https://www.11v11.com/players/marcus-barnes-256231/ |work=11v11.com |publisher=AFS Enterprises |accessdate=10 January 2018}}</ref> | birth_place = [[Reading, Berkshire|Reading]], England | height = {{height|m=1.85}}<ref name="11v11"/> | position = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]] | currentclub = [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] | clubnumber = 65 | youthyears1 = {{0|0000}}–2013| youthclubs1 = [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C. Development Squad and Academy|Wolverhampton Wanderers]] | youthyears2 = 2013–2015| youthclubs2 = [[Southampton F.C. Under-23s and Academy|Southampton]] | years1 = 2015– | clubs1 = [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] | caps1 = 0 | goals1 = 0 | years2 = 2018 | clubs2 = → [[Yeovil Town F.C.|Yeovil Town]] (loan)| caps2 = 8 | goals2 = 0 | club-update = 19:33, 5 May 2018 (UTC) }} '''Marcus Thomas Barnes''' (born 1 December 1996) is an English professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]] for [[Premier League]] club [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]]. He is the younger brother of [[Jamaica national football team|Jamaica]] international [[Giles Barnes]].
==Playing career== Barnes joined the [[Southampton F.C. Under-23s and Academy|Academy]] at [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] in September 2013, and signed his first professional contract upon turning 17 three months later after scoring six goals in his first 13 appearances for the under-18 team.<ref name="pro">{{cite web|title=Barnes signs pro deal|url=https://southamptonfc.com/news/2013-12-04/barnes-signs-pro-deal|accessdate=6 January 2018|publisher=Southampton FC|date=4 December 2013}}</ref> On 5 January 2018, he joined [[EFL League Two]] side [[Yeovil Town F.C.|Yeovil Town]] on loan until the end of the [[2017–18 Yeovil Town F.C. season|2017–18]] season.<ref>{{cite web|title=Yeovil Town: Corey Whelan, Lewis Wing and Marcus Barnes sign on loan|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42581783|accessdate=6 January 2018|publisher=BBC Sport|date=5 January 2018}}</ref> He made his competitive debut the following day against [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] in a Third Round [[FA Cup]] match at [[Huish Park]], scoring the opening goal in a 2–0 victory.<ref>{{cite web|title=Yeovil Town v Bradford City|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42519696|accessdate=6 January 2018|publisher=BBC Sport|date=6 January 2018}}</ref>
Barnes appeared as a substitute for the first team on 5 January 2019 in the [[FA Cup]] third round against [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] at [[Pride Park]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Derby 2–2 Southampton |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46706909 |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=5 January 2019 |date=5 January 2019}}</ref>
==Personal life== Barnes is of Jamaican descent.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/competitions/major-league-soccer/11912483/Giles-Barnes-sets-sights-on-2018-World-Cup-after-year-to-remember-for-Houston-Dynamo-and-Jamaica.html|title=Giles Barnes sets sights on 2018 World Cup after year to remember for Houston Dynamo and Jamaica|first=Bob|last=Williams|date=5 October 2015|work=Daily Telegraph|accessdate=10 January 2018}}</ref> He is the younger brother of [[Jamaica national football team|Jamaica]] international [[Giles Barnes]].<ref name="pro"/>
